","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/f995aa4b859d0cf0b0bdc85251f38ae52fee1678.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a35e6119002b7dd778e2ae0fb1e972a9ded8e019.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a30bebf76ae2f244ae392eed7db25e73e33a8f57.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"FirstColumnOnly,\u0022 \u0022SuppressEmptyColumns,\u0022 and \u0022TreeParentMember.\u0022 The \u0022Misc\u0022 section includes \u0022ValueColumn,\u0022 \u0022ValueDataStructure,\u0022 and \u0022ValueMethod\u0022 with the latter referencing \u0022Get Id.\u0022 The apparent purpose is to configure settings for a data service lookup related to priority management.\n\n\n  \n Save your changes, restart the Docker container with your server, and your drop-down menu will now be ordered according to the settings you applied: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/1/1bbe11732aac1070a02c6916449f5aa8e0d1ed87.png]\nDescription: The image features a user interface component displaying two dropdown menus labeled \u0022Priority\u0022 and \u0022Status.\u0022 The \u0022Priority\u0022 dropdown currently contains a text box with a selection menu showing three options: \u0022Low,\u0022 \u0022Mid,\u0022 and \u0022High.\u0022 The \u0022Status\u0022 label appears without a visible dropdown or options in the provided portion. The apparent purpose of this UI element is to allow users to set priority levels for tasks or items, enhancing task management within a software application.\n\n\n  \n   Default value setup \n If you want the drop-down menu to have a default value automatically set for every new record, follow this procedure. In this example, we will set the Status of any new Task to  New  by default. \n   Create a new Constant \n In the Model Browser, go to  Data  /  Constants , right-click on the package folder of your application, and create a new  Data Constant : \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/b2f74c7556097f3df714eecdd4a2f886af2a328f.png]\nDescription: The image depicts a software interface labeled \u0022Model Browser\u0022 for an application named \u0022myapplication.\u0022 In the left panel, under the \u0022Common\u0022 category, there is a subsection titled \u0022Data\u0022 containing a list of folder items including \u0022_spreadsheet,\u0022 \u0022_boolean,\u0022 \u0022_dates,\u0022 \u0022_guids,\u0022 \u0022_numbers,\u0022 \u0022_strings,\u0022 \u0022Attachments,\u0022 \u0022Dimensions,\u0022 and \u0022Model.\u0022 A dropdown context menu is displayed with options labeled \u0022New Group,\u0022 \u0022Repeat New,\u0022 and \u0022New\u0022 under the \u0022Data Constant\u0022 section. The menu appears to facilitate the organization or creation of new data constants within the application model.\n\n\n  \n   Set up the Constant \n Configure the following properties for the Constant: \n \n  Name : Name it \u201C YourEntity _ Value \u201D - this is our naming convention for Constants. \n  DataLookup : Select the Lookup related to the entity from which you want to take the value. \n  DataType : For items chosen from existing data, select  Uniqueidentifier . \n  Value : Select the value you want to set as the default. \n \n In our example, the Constant settings would look like this: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a73a17422b9bfc83672fe21487a451ac105912d4.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for a data constant labeled \u0022Status_New.\u0022 In the top section, it shows the context as \u0022Data Constant: Status_New.\u0022 The main content includes various fields: under \u0022(Info)\u0022 are subfields titled \u0022Schema Item\u0022 with \u0022Ancestors\u0022 marked as \u0022False,\u0022 \u0022Inheritable\u0022 as \u0022False,\u0022 and \u0022Name\u0022 as \u0022Status_New.\u0022 The \u0022Data Constant\u0022 section includes \u0022DataLookup\u0022 linked to \u0022Status_Name_GetId,\u0022 and \u0022DataType\u0022 specified as \u0022UniqueIdentifier.\u0022 The \u0022User Definition\u0022 part shows \u0022IsUserDefinable\u0022 as \u0022False\u0022 and \u0022UserDefinableDefaultConstant\u0022 also as \u0022False.\u0022 The \u0022Value\u0022 field is set to \u0022New.\u0022 The apparent purpose of the interface is to define and manage a data constant within a software application.\n\n\n  \n Save the constant. \n   Choose the Field \n In the Model Browser, go to  Data  /  Entities , expand the entity fields of your interest under your application\u2019s package folder, and double-click on the field where you want to set up the default value: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/f995aa4b859d0cf0b0bdc85251f38ae52fee1678.png]\nDescription: The image displays a Model Browser interface within a software application called \u0022myapplication.\u0022 The structure is hierarchical, containing sections labeled \u0022Common\u0022 and \u0022Data.\u0022 Under \u0022Data,\u0022 there are subsections for \u0022Constants,\u0022 \u0022Data Structures,\u0022 and \u0022Database Data Types,\u0022 with a folder named \u0022Entities.\u0022 Within \u0022Entities,\u0022 there are additional folders like \u0022__Origam General Interfaces,\u0022 \u0022__spreadsheet,\u0022 \u0022__system,\u0022 and \u0022Dimensions.","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:49:38"},"vector":[-0.047567192,-0.04366338,-0.07581633,-0.0027686576,0.00077284337,-0.043850146,0.04030847,0.011516614,-0.009539811,0.0047535547,-0.017592471,-0.04564608,-0.006781353,0.030629713,0.014395823,-0.0061903894,0.006530976,0.016314315,0.02017804,0.041320056,-0.02699446,-0.0029270719,0.06569569,0.031037237,-0.00014944177,0.050118353,-0.011028542,-0.024328021,-0.032979716,0.028179353,0.011991804,-0.04415264,-0.0014031086,-0.019028742,0.00